	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>University of Central Florida police officers further prepared for scenarios involving a shooter on campus Monday during a high-tech exercise with faculty and student role players.</p>
<p>While officers often train for emergency scenarios, the equipment and technical assistance provided for free by Saab Training USA and Octatron allows police to better evaluate the officers' responses.</p>
<p>Inside a vacant building near campus outfitted with Saab&rsquo;s Urban Training Package, officers participated in a first-of-its-kind exercise at a Florida state university. The Saab package provides seamless indoor tracking and captures the movements of officers and other role players with live cameras.</p>
<p>Officers, faculty and students donned Saab&rsquo;s five-pound vests equipped with GPS and radio communication that feeds data about player location, shots fired and much more to a command and control center called EXCON. The vests feature the Multiple Integrated Laser Engagement Systems, or MILES.</p>
<p>Police trainers and observers watched the scenario live on side-by-side screens. One featured a Saab software program that shows the whereabouts of the officers and other role players in the building, and the accompanying screen shows live video from cameras placed throughout the building.</p>
<p>The officers carried rifles that fired blanks and featured Saab&rsquo;s Small Arms Transmitters on the barrels. The transmitters sense when &ldquo;shots&rdquo; are fired. The lasers on the vests sense whether a shot produces a kill, a critical injury or a minor injury.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The high-tech equipment and the help of our students and faculty make this an invaluable experience for our police officers,&rdquo; said Lee Kernek, a UCF associate vice president who oversees the Police Department. &ldquo;While we hope that this type of scenario never happens on our campus, it is important that we provide frequent training to ensure that our officers are well prepared.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Monday&rsquo;s exercise gave about 20 faculty members and 120 students a rare inside look at a police training exercise. About three faculty members and 20 students volunteered as role players for each hour. Students were given cards indicating how they should respond after &ldquo;shots&rdquo; were fired &ndash; some were asked to crouch down under desks, while some would try to flee the building and others who were injured would grab onto officers pleading for help.</p>
<p>Officers entered the building in teams of four with a mission of finding and killing or capturing the shooter. Officers participated multiple times with different colleagues, and organizers made some changes &ndash; such as placing the shooter in a different room &ndash; so the scenarios would not become predictable.</p>
<p>Saab Training USA has conducted similar exercises for the Army, Marines, Navy SEALs and Department of Energy (Nuclear Power Plant Protective Forces). The software program is capable of displaying the whereabouts of up to 80 people at a time, and it can be configured to show the entire building or just one or two rooms.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Instead of going through the training and walking away, our software allows you and your trainers to keep going back over the scenarios to see what you did well and what you could have done differently,&rdquo; said Howard Harris, Saab Training USA&rsquo;s business development manager. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s a confidence builder.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The exercise was held in the vacant Graseby Building in the Central Florida Research Park adjacent to the UCF main campus. Desks and tables were placed inside to simulate classrooms and laboratories.</p>
<p>Octatron, a California company that provides systems encompassing areas of wireless communication, tactical equipment, security surveillance and emergency response, set up the live video camera system for the exercise.</p>
<p><b>Notable UCF Campus Security Initiatives:</b></p>
<p>-- Only state university with SWAT team</p>
<p>-- One of just five state universities with full-time emergency management coordinator</p>
<p>-- Preparing for installation of outdoor and indoor sirens/alert systems and text messaging systems.</p>
<hr />
<p>&nbsp;<b>About Saab Training USA:</b> Saab Training USA is located in Central Florida&rsquo;s Research Park and supports the U.S. Marines, U.S. Army, U.S. Navy SEALs, and Department of Homeland Defense with laser based and other training products and services.&nbsp; The company has long been a leader in producing quality training systems, ranging from high tech laser equipment to targets to large-scale instrumentation systems to track, record and produce After Action Reviews.</p>
<p><b>UCF Stands For Opportunity:</b> The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 6th largest in the nation with more than 48,000 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
		
			
		
	
		
			
		
	
		
			
		
	
